'''Tsukahara Kofun''' (塚原古墳)
* {{ill|Tsukahara Kofun Group (Tama)|ja|塚原古墳群 (多摩市)|12=draft}} - Located in {{ill|Tama, Tokyo|ja|多摩市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo Prefecture|ja|東京都|12=draft}} in the Wada area. A kofun group from the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Tsukahara Kofun Group (Iida)|ja|塚原古墳群 (飯田市)|12=draft}} - Located in {{ill|Iida, Nagano|ja|飯田市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft}}. Includes the Tsukahara Futagotsuka Kofun, a 67-meter-long keyhole-shaped kofun designated as a city historic site. * {{ill|Tsukahara Kofun (Shima)|ja|塚原古墳 (志摩市)|12=draft}} - A circular kofun that once existed in {{ill|Shima, Mie|ja|志摩市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft}}, now lost. * {{ill|Tsukahara Kofun Group (Takatsuki)|ja|塚原古墳群 (高槻市)|12=draft}} - Located in {{ill|Takatsuki|ja|高槻市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}}. Once included 15 groups with about 110 kofun, collectively called Tsukahara Yajōzuka. Discovered by {{ill|William Gowland|ja|ウィリアム・ゴーランド|12=draft}} in 1872, these kofun were pivotal in early research of ancient Kofuns. * {{ill|Tsukahara Kofun Group (Kumamoto)|ja|塚原古墳群 (熊本市)|12=draft}} - Located in {{ill|Minami-ku, Kumamoto|ja|熊本市南区|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kumamoto Prefecture|ja|熊本県|12=draft}}. A designated National Historic Site, developed as Tsukahara Kofun Park with 77 Kofuns including keyhole-shaped, square-ditch, and circular kofun. Surveys suggest around 500 kofun may exist in the area, with 203 confirmed. * {{ill|Iwahara Kofun Group|ja|岩原古墳群|12=draft}} (Tsukahara Kofun in Yamaga) - Part of the Iwahara Kofun Group in {{ill|Yamaga, Kumamoto|ja|山鹿市|12=draft}}, Kumamoto. Consists of nine circular Kofuns designated as a National Historic Site. Nearby are the Iwahara Horizontal Burial Chambers, a prefectural historic site.
{{aimai}}
